Political Appointees in Niger state with the ambition to contest in the 2023 general elections have been directed by the state All Progressives Congress (APC) to resign before the end of Friday. Political appointees who are accredited delegates for the APC National Convention were also asked to resign from their respective positions. This was contained in a statement signed by the state party Secretary, Ibrahim Aliyu Khaleel and made available to newsmen in Minna on Thursday. The APC Secretary stated that this is in line with the Electoral Act amendment bill which was recently signed into law stressing that it is constitutional and should be adhered to.   Wike and political asylum seekers in Edo     2023: Atiku’s zoning formula     Businessman Dauda joins 2023 presidential race   “According to the decision of our great party to hold her national convention on the 26th of March and the signing into law of the Electoral Act amendment bill 2022, we hereby direct all political appointees interested in contesting any elective position to tender their resignation within this week. “Similarly, all accredited state delegates are to resign from any political position they are presently occupying within the same period. “This is a constitutional matter that must be respected by all party members in the state. We hereby advise all intending party members to comply with the constitutional provision and party directives towards upholding the mission and vision of the party. “We further urge all affected party faithful to submit their resignation letters to the office of Secretary to the state government and the APC secretariat in Minna,” the statement read.